WEBVTT

00:13.056 --> 00:15.624
(ETHEREAL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:27.336 --> 00:29.005
Turn to the right,
milady.

00:29.072 --> 00:30.405
Thank you.

00:35.912 --> 00:37.312
That's it.

00:55.330 --> 00:57.299
(WIND WHISTLING)

01:01.004 --> 01:02.906
(CROWD CHATTERING)

01:05.942 --> 01:09.444
HERALD: Hear ye,
hear ye, hear ye!

01:10.013 --> 01:14.751
Lords! Knights! Squires!

01:14.818 --> 01:17.887
And all other
manner of people.

01:17.954 --> 01:21.858
That by the command of Our
Lord, the king of France,

01:21.925 --> 01:25.661
it is strictly prohibited,

01:25.728 --> 01:29.631
on pain of death
and the loss of property,

01:29.698 --> 01:32.501
for anyone here
to be armed,

01:32.568 --> 01:34.871
or to carry
a sword or dagger

01:34.938 --> 01:38.842
unless he be one who has
the express permission

01:39.641 --> 01:41.543
of Our Lord, the king.

01:43.412 --> 01:45.849
Each man is to fight

01:45.915 --> 01:48.718
on horseback and on foot,

01:48.785 --> 01:50.452
armed in the manner
that pleases him,

01:50.519 --> 01:53.689
with any weapon or device
of attack or defense.

01:53.756 --> 01:58.560
Except for weapons or
devices of equal design

01:59.561 --> 02:02.431
or made with
charms or spells

02:02.497 --> 02:06.035
or any other thing that is
forbidden by God and holy church

02:06.102 --> 02:07.971
to all good Christians.

02:09.604 --> 02:12.574
If either combatant should
carry onto the field of battle

02:12.641 --> 02:16.112
any arms that have been
forged with spells,

02:16.179 --> 02:19.949
charms, enchantments,
or any other evil arts,

02:20.016 --> 02:23.953
then so shall the malefactor
be punished as an enemy of God

02:25.054 --> 02:26.622
or as a traitor

02:28.423 --> 02:29.893
or as a murderer.

02:32.061 --> 02:34.163
- JACQUES: Tighter. Tighter.
- SERVANT: <i>Monsieur.</i>

02:46.175 --> 02:48.077
(CROWS CAWING)

02:54.817 --> 02:56.753
(DOG BARKING)

03:10.565 --> 03:11.868
(PIERRE INHALES SHARPLY)

03:12.769 --> 03:13.870
(HORSE GALLOPING)

03:29.618 --> 03:32.454
MAN: Knights, proceed.

03:38.194 --> 03:40.229
(SOFT TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

03:54.509 --> 03:56.545
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

04:00.817 --> 04:02.952
- MAN 2: Let them go!
- (HORSE NEIGHS)

04:03.019 --> 04:06.889
- Let them go! Let them go!
- (CROWD CHEERING)

04:06.956 --> 04:08.925
(DRAMATIC MUSIC CONTINUES)

04:14.797 --> 04:16.065
(CHEERING FADES OFF)

04:18.701 --> 04:19.736
(GRUNTS)

04:32.715 --> 04:35.284
MAN: (LOUDLY)
Come for your fight!

04:35.351 --> 04:37.686
You're all gonna die!

04:38.921 --> 04:41.858
You're all gonna die
like pigs!

04:43.692 --> 04:45.928
- Come on, then!
- (WOMEN WEEPING)

04:45.995 --> 04:48.798
- Come on, you failed scum...
- (WOMAN PLEADING)

04:48.865 --> 04:49.932
We cannot
just sit here.

04:49.999 --> 04:51.234
MAN: ...and fight!

04:51.301 --> 04:53.535
Jean, we were ordered by
Pierre to hold this bridge.

04:53.602 --> 04:55.537
Orders be damned.
For the king.

04:55.604 --> 04:57.073
(WOMEN CRYING AND SHRIEKING)

04:57.140 --> 04:58.841
JEAN: For the king!

04:59.674 --> 05:00.810
MEN: For the king!

05:00.877 --> 05:02.544
(ALL SHOUTING)

05:06.315 --> 05:08.550
(ALL CONTINUE SHOUTING)

05:11.721 --> 05:13.923
(ALL GRUNTING AND YELLING)

05:41.918 --> 05:42.952
Thank you.

05:49.658 --> 05:53.595
JEAN: I will make no apology
for how you men fought today.

05:54.663 --> 05:56.766
It was an honor
to be there with you.

05:58.201 --> 06:00.903
Limoges is lost.

06:00.970 --> 06:03.773
And our allies have failed
to take the port at Brest.

06:04.907 --> 06:07.176
Our new Lord, Pierre,

06:07.243 --> 06:10.880
has now resigned the campaign
and orders us home.

06:11.380 --> 06:12.982
We move at dawn.

06:13.349 --> 06:15.084
MEN: Hear, hear.

06:15.151 --> 06:16.119
MAN: To the king.

06:18.855 --> 06:21.257
Evidently,
Pierre is not happy.

06:23.926 --> 06:25.161
Lives were saved.

06:25.228 --> 06:27.396
Not in Limoges.

06:27.463 --> 06:29.832
Let us return home,
my friend.

06:30.933 --> 06:32.735
You saved
my life today.

06:34.837 --> 06:36.139
Thank you.

06:37.807 --> 06:40.176
(MAN SINGING FRENCH FOLK SONG)

06:48.451 --> 06:51.087
(CONTINUES SINGING)

06:58.961 --> 07:00.997
(ALL TOAST, CHATTERING)

07:02.832 --> 07:04.033
- (DOGS BARKING)
- (HORSES APPROACHING)

07:04.100 --> 07:05.735
(HORSE WHINNYING)

07:11.774 --> 07:13.309
GATEKEEPER: Declare yourself!

07:14.076 --> 07:16.212
Squire Jean de Carrouges.

07:16.279 --> 07:18.347
Son of the captain
of this fort.

07:18.414 --> 07:20.049
GATEKEEPER: Open the gates!

07:21.951 --> 07:22.985
(MAN URGING HORSE)

07:34.230 --> 07:36.899
(PLEASANT MUSIC PLAYING)

07:36.966 --> 07:38.201
It's a great honor
for Pierre

07:38.268 --> 07:40.169
to have chosen your father's
castle for this ceremony.

07:40.236 --> 07:42.805
I shall be prepared
to assume this captaincy

07:42.872 --> 07:44.907
upon my father's passing.

07:44.974 --> 07:46.375
Pray it is not
for many years.

07:46.442 --> 07:48.711
Father. Mother.

07:48.778 --> 07:50.746
Captain. Milady.

07:50.813 --> 07:52.481
Squires.

07:52.548 --> 07:54.350
Do not keep Our
Lord Pierre waiting.

07:54.417 --> 07:56.018
MAN 1: ...become your man.
I shall serve you for life.

07:59.789 --> 08:03.025
MAN 2: So, Lord, I become your man.
I swear I shall serve you for life.

08:04.827 --> 08:08.898
MAN 3: Milord, I become your man.
I shall serve you for life.

08:08.965 --> 08:11.734
MAN 4: Milord, I become your man.
I swear I shall serve you for life.

08:17.873 --> 08:20.810
Lord, I become your man.
I swear I shall serve you for life.

08:28.184 --> 08:29.218
- Lord...
- PIERRE: Closer.

08:32.255 --> 08:34.289
Lord,
I become your man.

08:34.357 --> 08:36.292
I swear I shall
serve you for life.

08:39.996 --> 08:41.330
(SIGHS)

08:42.365 --> 08:44.400
- (HORSE WHINNIES)
- (MAN URGING HORSE)

08:45.935 --> 08:48.371
(DOGS BARKING)

08:51.274 --> 08:52.541
Declare yourself.

08:53.976 --> 08:55.978
It is I.
Helen of Troy.

08:56.812 --> 08:58.014
(LAUGHS)

08:59.081 --> 09:00.483
Le Gris.

09:01.884 --> 09:03.819
JACQUES: It's good to see
you, my friend.

09:05.221 --> 09:07.490
Though I do not come
only as a friend.

09:09.292 --> 09:12.295
I'm afraid there's more to
my visit than I have let on.

09:16.299 --> 09:17.566
Speak.

09:20.469 --> 09:23.239
Pierre has charged me with
the collection of debts.

09:23.472 --> 09:25.408
I see.

09:25.474 --> 09:29.045
I have already visited all the
other tenants in his domain.

09:30.613 --> 09:32.181
And now...

09:32.248 --> 09:33.349
You have come
to see me.

09:33.416 --> 09:35.384
I have come
to see you.

09:39.922 --> 09:43.359
These levies are
for military defense.

09:43.426 --> 09:45.928
And you know as well as
anyone our enemy's present.

09:45.995 --> 09:47.296
And we need to be ready.

09:47.363 --> 09:48.898
When have I not been ready to
stand and fight for my king?

09:48.964 --> 09:50.499
JACQUES: You have.

09:50.566 --> 09:53.202
More than any other.

09:53.269 --> 09:54.937
But that's not all
this Pierre wants.

09:55.004 --> 09:56.205
No, what Pierre wants...

09:56.272 --> 09:58.074
Pierre wants the money
that he's rightfully owed.

10:04.180 --> 10:06.382
I don't have it.

10:06.449 --> 10:08.517
This plague has carried
off half my workforce.

10:08.584 --> 10:10.152
My rent collection
is down.

10:10.219 --> 10:11.620
My fields yield half
what they used to.

10:11.687 --> 10:14.023
And the cost of labor
has now risen.

10:14.490 --> 10:15.891
Yes.

10:19.061 --> 10:21.464
How is it the other
vassals paid?

10:21.530 --> 10:23.866
They paid because
I had to insist.

10:24.333 --> 10:26.102
I see.

10:26.168 --> 10:28.237
And now,
you insist upon me?

10:32.541 --> 10:33.576
Let me talk to Pierre.

10:36.078 --> 10:38.314
He's not without reason.

10:38.381 --> 10:40.116
I will explain
your situation.

10:41.050 --> 10:43.185
You are a true friend.

10:43.252 --> 10:45.554
But I cannot return
empty-handed.

10:45.621 --> 10:47.089
Of course not.

10:49.558 --> 10:51.093
Thank you.

10:52.561 --> 10:54.230
Let me see
what I have at hand.

11:02.538 --> 11:04.407
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

11:16.152 --> 11:17.686
- JACQUES: Think about this.
- I have.

11:17.754 --> 11:18.988
You have not.

11:19.055 --> 11:20.489
I will be fighting
under Admiral de Vienne.

11:20.556 --> 11:23.292
The English are looting the
Cotentin Peninsula as we speak.

11:23.359 --> 11:24.960
This plague has taken
your wife and son.

11:25.027 --> 11:26.095
JEAN: I will not stand by
whilst Lower Normandy falls.

11:26.162 --> 11:27.630
Do not let
this obduracy take you.

11:27.697 --> 11:29.131
You have no heir.

11:29.198 --> 11:31.333
If you die, all you have
will revert to Count Pierre.

11:32.535 --> 11:34.537
A fact not lost on
Pierre, I'm certain.

11:34.603 --> 11:36.205
He does not favor me
as he does you.

11:36.272 --> 11:37.473
JACQUES: No,
you have much to live for.

11:37.540 --> 11:39.408
What do I have to live for, here?
What?

11:39.475 --> 11:41.143
A name.

11:41.210 --> 11:45.080
It's too great and storied a name
for you to treat it so recklessly.

11:45.147 --> 11:47.383
Your father has
the captaincy of Belleme.

11:47.450 --> 11:49.251
When he dies,
you will inherit that garrison

11:49.318 --> 11:50.553
and everything that
comes with it.

11:50.619 --> 11:53.155
And I am your friend.

11:53.222 --> 11:56.525
And there are many others like me
who would prefer you not perish.

11:58.127 --> 12:01.697
I don't embark on this
campaign recklessly.

12:01.765 --> 12:03.499
I don't embark on it
just to fight.

12:04.099 --> 12:05.401
Then why?

12:06.135 --> 12:08.037
(SCOFFS) Jacques.

12:10.473 --> 12:11.674
I am

12:13.108 --> 12:14.310
broke.

12:16.045 --> 12:17.346
I need money.

12:19.381 --> 12:21.283
(ALL GRUNTING AND YELLING)

13:05.762 --> 13:09.365
- (MAN SCREAMING)
- (HORSE SQUEALS)

13:09.431 --> 13:10.466
(UPBEAT MEDIEVAL MUSIC
PLAYING)

13:10.533 --> 13:13.235
TOWNSPEOPLE:
Long live the king!

13:14.637 --> 13:16.539
Long live the king!

13:24.748 --> 13:26.081
(CHEERING CONTINUES)

13:29.251 --> 13:31.387
(UPBEAT MEDIEVAL MUSIC
CONTINUES)

13:34.590 --> 13:36.625
MAN 1: They're back!
Quick! Come on! They're back!

13:36.692 --> 13:38.627
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

13:41.664 --> 13:43.098
(LAUGHTER)

13:49.839 --> 13:51.106
WOMAN 1: I'll take
that from you.

13:51.173 --> 13:52.842
WOMAN 2:
Let me help you, sir.

13:52.909 --> 13:54.744
WOMAN 3: Turn around,
please, my lord.

13:54.811 --> 13:56.312
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

13:57.814 --> 13:59.716
WOMAN 4:
Lift, lift your arm.

14:01.785 --> 14:03.519
WOMAN: Take them more bread.

14:03.586 --> 14:05.254
Over here.
They want some more.

14:05.321 --> 14:06.790
(INDISTINCT CHATTER CONTINUES)

14:06.856 --> 14:08.825
(MUFFLED MUSIC PLAYING)

14:10.225 --> 14:12.428
(MEN SINGING IN FRENCH)

14:12.494 --> 14:14.463
(UPBEAT MEDIEVAL MUSIC
PLAYING)

14:15.598 --> 14:17.232
(SINGING CONTINUES)

14:24.206 --> 14:26.308
Robert de Thibouville.

14:26.375 --> 14:29.211
He's providing shelter
and vittles for us.

14:30.346 --> 14:32.816
De Thibouville?

14:32.882 --> 14:35.651
Did he not side with the
English against us at Poitiers?

14:35.719 --> 14:38.354
Yes, but he was pardoned
along with the others.

14:38.420 --> 14:40.189
He's with us now.

14:40.255 --> 14:42.591
And he'll stay that way if
he knows what's good for him.

14:42.658 --> 14:43.893
Steady, Jean.

14:43.960 --> 14:45.829
It's a roof
over our heads.

14:45.895 --> 14:47.663
Besides,

14:47.731 --> 14:50.132
he has quite
the wine cellar.

14:57.473 --> 14:59.508
(LIVELY CHATTER AND LAUGHTER)

15:05.882 --> 15:07.349
JEAN: What a beauty.

15:09.218 --> 15:10.653
She is
a de Thibouville?

15:10.720 --> 15:13.389
Yes. Her name is
even older than yours.

15:13.455 --> 15:15.424
She's his only daughter.

15:15.491 --> 15:17.593
There's a dowry
to be had.

15:17.660 --> 15:18.895
Of course, a man would
have to bear the mark

15:18.962 --> 15:20.462
of her father's
disgrace...

15:20.529 --> 15:23.465
I don't imagine one
would suffer too greatly

15:23.532 --> 15:25.300
at the task of
producing an heir.

15:27.569 --> 15:29.672
Gentlemen, welcome.

15:29.739 --> 15:31.407
You fought bravely.

15:32.508 --> 15:33.843
Thank you for hosting us.

15:33.910 --> 15:36.846
- I would like to introduce...
- Jean de Carrouges.

15:36.913 --> 15:38.715
Your reputation
precedes you.

15:38.782 --> 15:40.817
As does yours.

15:40.884 --> 15:41.785
(ROBERT CHUCKLES)

15:41.851 --> 15:44.486
It's my pleasure to
host you and your men.

15:44.553 --> 15:47.489
It is only just to support the
men who fight for the king.

15:49.324 --> 15:51.861
Some lessons are learned
later in life, hmm?

15:51.928 --> 15:53.897
(MEN SINGING INDISTINCTLY)

15:54.898 --> 15:56.800
Allow me to introduce
my daughter.

15:56.866 --> 15:58.400
Marguerite.

15:58.467 --> 16:01.336
Marguerite, this is
Squire Jean de Carrouges.

16:02.504 --> 16:05.240
Milady, I'm pleased
to meet you.

16:06.308 --> 16:07.844
Pleasure is mine.

16:07.911 --> 16:09.611
(MEN CONTINUE SINGING)

16:18.687 --> 16:21.925
ROBERT: The dowry
includes this parcel as well.

16:21.991 --> 16:24.626
Starting at
the hunting grounds.

16:30.265 --> 16:32.534
JEAN: What of this here?
The one to the north?

16:33.402 --> 16:35.237
Aunou-le-Faucon.

16:39.308 --> 16:42.511
As I say, starting at
the hunting grounds.

16:53.622 --> 16:55.691
JEAN: I'll have
that piece of land as well.

16:56.625 --> 16:58.627
Most certainly.

16:59.428 --> 17:01.030
(BELL TOLLS DISTANTLY)

17:02.664 --> 17:05.702
(PRIEST CHANTING IN LATIN)

17:13.407 --> 17:15.912
ALL: Amen.

17:34.596 --> 17:36.032
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

17:36.099 --> 17:38.835
(DRUMS BEATING)

17:38.902 --> 17:41.037
(APPLAUSE)

17:41.104 --> 17:43.807
- (LIVELY MEDIEVAL MUSIC PLAYS)
- (LAUGHTER)

17:50.079 --> 17:51.480
(INAUDIBLE CONVERSATION)

17:57.486 --> 18:00.023
I'm a very
jealous man, milady.

18:00.089 --> 18:03.325
Tonight, you are mine and
will dance with no other.

18:04.693 --> 18:06.896
And every night
hereafter.

18:06.963 --> 18:08.932
(LIVELY MEDIEVAL MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

18:10.066 --> 18:11.366
(WOMAN WHOOPS)

18:12.634 --> 18:14.670
(HOLY WATER SLOSHING)

18:22.511 --> 18:25.014
(PRIEST CHANTING IN LATIN)

18:26.783 --> 18:28.517
(HOLY WATER SLOSHING)

18:42.832 --> 18:44.600
No need to worry.

18:49.605 --> 18:51.040
JACQUES: This is it.

18:56.411 --> 18:57.479
(GOATS BLEATING)

18:57.546 --> 18:59.082
Property starts
at the river mouth

18:59.148 --> 19:02.451
and extends all the way
to the hill beyond.

19:02.517 --> 19:05.420
JEAN: So, this is
Aunou-le-Faucon.

19:05.487 --> 19:08.457
This was meant to be
part of Marguerite's dowry.

19:08.523 --> 19:10.425
She loved it here.

19:10.492 --> 19:12.594
And Pierre simply
gave it to you.

19:12.661 --> 19:14.931
In appreciation
of my service.

19:16.766 --> 19:19.102
His accounts were
in complete chaos.

19:19.168 --> 19:22.105
Once I was able to reorder
them and collect the rents due,

19:22.171 --> 19:25.407
everything started functioning
properly, and his fortunes turned.

19:25.474 --> 19:28.610
Gave me this as a
sign of his gratitude.

19:33.149 --> 19:34.717
It's not my doing.

19:34.784 --> 19:36.886
The count is generous
and impetuous.

19:36.953 --> 19:38.487
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

19:42.859 --> 19:44.593
Let us eat.

19:53.002 --> 19:55.972
MARGUERITE: I wish you'd seen
the gardens at Aunou-le-Faucon.

19:56.039 --> 19:58.808
We had roses and lavender.

19:58.875 --> 20:00.944
Then, we shall
have those here.

20:01.010 --> 20:04.814
I remember my father built a swing
on the largest tree in the estate.

20:04.881 --> 20:09.052
I will find the largest
tree and do the same.

20:09.118 --> 20:12.055
I have such wonderful
memories of my summers there.

20:12.121 --> 20:14.824
(TENDER MUSIC PLAYING)

20:14.891 --> 20:19.729
JEAN: (SIGHS) It's a pity Pierre
took that estate from your father.

20:19.796 --> 20:21.798
I know you miss it.

20:21.864 --> 20:25.902
It's the only way he
could pay what he owed.

20:25.969 --> 20:29.706
Pierre then just gave it
to Jacques Le Gris as a gift.

20:30.672 --> 20:33.209
Do all squires enjoy
such lavish gifts?

20:33.977 --> 20:36.678
Le Gris more
than most.

20:36.746 --> 20:39.581
He has become
Pierre's most trusted.

20:41.217 --> 20:44.187
Perhaps Aunou-le-Faucon
is not gone for good.

20:46.289 --> 20:48.690
Perhaps I shall not
let that rest.

20:50.193 --> 20:52.095
Jean.

20:52.161 --> 20:54.263
My love, I have
bled for this king.

20:55.031 --> 20:56.265
He knows of me.

20:57.632 --> 21:00.136
I may have more power
than you think.

21:00.203 --> 21:02.637
I know how powerful
you are.

21:04.207 --> 21:06.075
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

21:06.142 --> 21:09.812
This land was promised to me
as part of my wife's dowry.

21:10.880 --> 21:13.950
The petition
is denied.

21:14.017 --> 21:18.087
This decision comes directly
from His Majesty, the king.

21:18.154 --> 21:19.722
(PEOPLE SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

21:19.789 --> 21:21.024
(WOMAN URGING ANIMALS)

21:22.025 --> 21:23.558
(HORSE WHINNIES)

21:24.327 --> 21:25.962
(DUCKS QUACKING)

21:30.266 --> 21:32.667
Are you
Squire Jean de Carrouges?

21:32.735 --> 21:33.936
That is I.

21:35.938 --> 21:37.140
What does it say?

21:37.206 --> 21:38.607
'Tis your father.

21:38.673 --> 21:40.009
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

21:40.076 --> 21:41.643
(HORSE WHINNIES)

21:46.916 --> 21:49.285
(WOMAN YELLING IN FRENCH)

21:54.090 --> 21:55.690
JEAN: Open the gate!

21:55.758 --> 21:57.093
Open the gate!

21:57.160 --> 21:58.261
(HORSE NEIGHS)

22:00.096 --> 22:01.596
JEAN: Leave us.

22:01.663 --> 22:02.965
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

22:09.671 --> 22:11.941
I was in Paris
when the news came.

22:14.609 --> 22:16.746
Your father died quietly.

22:16.813 --> 22:18.214
In his sleep.

22:20.850 --> 22:22.185
I am lost.

22:23.886 --> 22:26.255
They tell me I'm to leave
here within a month.

22:28.991 --> 22:31.294
You will do
no such thing.

22:31.360 --> 22:33.296
I will assume
the captaincy.

22:33.362 --> 22:34.997
You will keep your
quarters, your servants.

22:35.064 --> 22:36.132
Everything will be
the way it was...

22:36.199 --> 22:38.101
Jean, have you
not heard?

22:38.167 --> 22:40.369
You're not going to follow
in your father's footsteps

22:40.436 --> 22:43.072
as captain here
at Belleme.

22:43.139 --> 22:45.208
What do you mean?

22:45.274 --> 22:49.345
Why did you have to sue the
count for a piece of land?

22:49.412 --> 22:51.380
Just to impress
your bride.

22:51.447 --> 22:54.283
That land was promised to me.
It was an appeal.

22:54.350 --> 22:56.352
And now, you've made an
enemy of Count Pierre.

22:56.419 --> 22:57.920
It was right.

22:57.987 --> 23:01.690
(SCOFFS) Right.
There's no right.

23:01.757 --> 23:04.093
There is only
the power of men.

23:06.329 --> 23:09.832
You sued him,
and you've made a powerful enemy.

23:12.068 --> 23:13.703
Your father was
a hard man

23:13.769 --> 23:16.973
but there was much about this
world that he understood.

23:21.277 --> 23:26.349
Who then will assume
my father's captaincy?

23:33.122 --> 23:35.191
(SOFT DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

23:50.373 --> 23:52.241
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

23:59.148 --> 24:00.383
PIERRE: Good day!

24:02.118 --> 24:04.187
Join us, my squire.

24:04.253 --> 24:05.855
This is a day
for celebration.

24:08.925 --> 24:11.727
I will not be
staying, milord.

24:11.794 --> 24:14.397
I do not wish to interrupt
such an occasion,

24:15.898 --> 24:18.334
but my honor
compels me to speak.

24:21.971 --> 24:25.107
I was angered,
but I spoke well.

24:25.174 --> 24:26.943
I said to Pierre,

24:27.009 --> 24:30.313
"Can you stand there,
as a man of honor, as my liege lord,

24:30.379 --> 24:33.316
"and say that I am not man enough
to assume my rightful captaincy

24:33.382 --> 24:37.486
"that my grandfather and my father
held for the last 20 years of his life

24:37.553 --> 24:39.155
"and take command
of that garrison

24:39.222 --> 24:41.791
"and hold the fort of
Belleme for my king?"

24:41.857 --> 24:42.959
And what said Pierre?

24:43.025 --> 24:44.894
And there was Le Gris,

24:44.961 --> 24:48.197
whose life I saved,
sitting by his side

24:48.264 --> 24:51.234
with his captaincy,
not even man enough to look at me.

24:52.335 --> 24:54.904
He poisons milord
with evil advice.

24:54.971 --> 24:57.273
Whispered in his ear,
blackening my name.

24:57.340 --> 24:58.341
(CHUCKLES DRYLY)

24:59.475 --> 25:01.477
Surely, you did not
say this.

25:03.813 --> 25:05.815
You did.

25:10.519 --> 25:12.388
We are no longer welcome
at court.

25:13.222 --> 25:14.390
Jean...

25:14.457 --> 25:15.491
So be it.

25:18.394 --> 25:19.629
(GOAT BLEATING)

25:23.466 --> 25:25.501
- (ROOSTER CROWS)
- (DOG BARKING)

25:34.076 --> 25:35.911
Milord.

25:35.978 --> 25:37.880
Jean, an invitation
has arrived.

25:40.249 --> 25:43.085
Your friend Jean Crespin
has invited us to his home.

25:43.152 --> 25:45.488
They are celebrating the
birth of their first child.

25:46.389 --> 25:48.457
It's a boy.

25:48.524 --> 25:50.459
Oh, wonderful news.

25:50.526 --> 25:52.228
It's been a year
since Belleme.

25:53.929 --> 25:55.498
Perhaps we may
show our faces

25:55.564 --> 25:58.200
so they know we carry on
in spite of this injustice.

25:59.435 --> 26:01.937
A healthy child
in these times

26:02.004 --> 26:04.106
is cause for
a celebration.

26:06.142 --> 26:10.479
Do you think I would deny
the rabble of Argentan

26:10.546 --> 26:13.082
the sight of
a true noblewoman?

26:14.450 --> 26:16.319
Have a gown made.

26:21.624 --> 26:23.092
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

26:27.296 --> 26:30.199
MAN: This one is ready.
We need more hay over here.

26:37.440 --> 26:39.475
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

26:48.351 --> 26:50.386
(MERRY MEDIEVAL MUSIC
PLAYING IN DISTANCE)

27:00.262 --> 27:02.365
I am very glad
you chose to attend.

27:02.431 --> 27:05.368
This will only do you
good, my love.

27:05.434 --> 27:08.070
Jean, I'm very pleased to see you.
It's been a long time.

27:08.137 --> 27:10.005
Congratulations, my friend.

27:10.072 --> 27:11.540
- Milady, you look lovely.
- Thank you.

27:11.607 --> 27:13.509
Please, you're
most welcome.

27:13.576 --> 27:15.911
(MERRY MEDIEVAL MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

27:19.582 --> 27:20.983
(LAUGHTER)

27:23.052 --> 27:24.954
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

27:31.994 --> 27:33.396
Pardon me, milady.

27:40.436 --> 27:42.004
- (MUSIC ENDS)
- (APPLAUSE)

27:45.441 --> 27:48.010
- Le Gris.
- Carrouges.

27:48.077 --> 27:51.380
Pax! Well done!
Well done, all!

27:51.447 --> 27:53.983
Let there be no ill will among
the servants of the king.

27:54.049 --> 27:55.117
He needs us all
right now.

27:55.184 --> 27:57.920
Hear, hear.
Well spoken, old friend.

27:57.987 --> 27:59.121
Marguerite, come.

27:59.188 --> 28:00.389
Give our old friend
a kiss

28:00.456 --> 28:03.025
and show the good faith
of the house Carrouges.

28:07.062 --> 28:08.998
(APPLAUSE CONTINUES)

28:25.114 --> 28:27.349
I will return in just a few
months, my love.

28:27.416 --> 28:29.719
I will be safe and well attended
to by Alice and your mother,

28:29.786 --> 28:31.220
but I will miss you.

28:31.287 --> 28:32.321
This is what I do.

28:33.222 --> 28:34.423
Let me provide for you.

28:34.490 --> 28:36.459
And what of you?

28:36.525 --> 28:38.494
I have all
that I need.

28:38.561 --> 28:40.229
Except an heir.

28:40.696 --> 28:41.731
My love.

28:42.465 --> 28:44.133
(KISSES)

28:44.200 --> 28:45.668
It comes
as God wills it.

28:53.609 --> 28:55.644
(SOMBER STRING MUSIC PLAYING)

29:12.461 --> 29:15.331
Be thou a knight
in the name of God.

29:16.298 --> 29:17.466
Rise.

29:17.533 --> 29:19.502
(ALL CHEERING)

29:19.568 --> 29:21.303
Jean de Carrouges!

29:23.372 --> 29:25.441
In honor of your service
to our king.

29:26.175 --> 29:27.476
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

29:29.445 --> 29:30.546
Quiet!

29:30.613 --> 29:32.381
- (HORSE WHINNIES)
- (CHATTERING STOPS)

29:35.251 --> 29:37.553
Be thou a knight
in the name of God.

29:38.220 --> 29:39.355
Rise.

29:47.296 --> 29:51.300
All right, men!
Make preparations for battle!

30:08.551 --> 30:09.685
Sire?

30:19.361 --> 30:20.596
(WEAPON FIRES SOFTLY)

30:20.663 --> 30:22.498
(FAINT WHOOSHING)

30:24.600 --> 30:26.302
(GROANING)

30:26.368 --> 30:28.203
(MEN CLAMORING)

30:30.239 --> 30:31.507
(SHOUTS)
Why do they run?

30:32.474 --> 30:33.609
Why do they run?

30:33.676 --> 30:35.745
(PAINED SCREAMING)

30:36.846 --> 30:38.514
For the king!

30:38.581 --> 30:40.082
(ALL YELLING)

30:43.552 --> 30:45.487
(ALL GRUNTING)

30:51.193 --> 30:53.596
- (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)
- BOY: Our lord returns!

30:53.662 --> 30:55.497
They're coming!

30:55.564 --> 30:58.100
Our lord returns!

30:58.167 --> 31:00.636
- (HORSE WHINNIES)
- Our lord returns! (GRUNTS)

31:05.274 --> 31:07.443
- (BELL RINGING)
- Our lord returns!

31:07.509 --> 31:09.111
He's coming!

31:15.150 --> 31:16.720
(TRUMPET BLOWING FANFARE)

31:21.390 --> 31:23.459
Welcome back, sire!

31:23.525 --> 31:25.494
(DRAMATIC MUSIC CONTINUES)

31:32.769 --> 31:34.236
(SIGHS HAPPILY)

31:40.376 --> 31:41.811
(MARGUERITE CRYING SOFTLY)

31:52.221 --> 31:54.423
(JEAN COUGHING)

31:55.624 --> 31:59.194
MARGUERITE: Milord,
you are not well.

31:59.261 --> 32:03.399
This fever is all I've brought back
from that wretched place. (COUGHS)

32:03.465 --> 32:05.300
As well as
your knighthood.

32:06.535 --> 32:08.337
Tomorrow,
I must go to Paris.

32:09.571 --> 32:10.639
I'll be away one week.

32:10.707 --> 32:11.741
What do you want?

32:11.808 --> 32:13.409
I'm owed money
by the treasurer.

32:13.475 --> 32:14.811
Jean, you are unwell.

32:14.878 --> 32:16.512
He's well enough
to travel.

32:17.680 --> 32:18.948
To Paris?

32:19.015 --> 32:20.582
That's three days' ride.

32:20.649 --> 32:22.451
JEAN: And Argentan.

32:22.518 --> 32:24.954
Duty demands that
I report to Pierre.

32:26.555 --> 32:28.457
They will admire you
as a knight.

32:29.425 --> 32:30.727
And you will confound

32:30.794 --> 32:32.929
those who had not expected
you to return, Sir Jean.

32:35.965 --> 32:37.666
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

32:39.568 --> 32:41.905
(JEAN COUGHING)

32:43.405 --> 32:44.908
(PEOPLE SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

32:44.974 --> 32:47.242
(SOFT MEDIEVAL MUSIC PLAYING)

32:54.784 --> 32:56.452
(DOG BARKING)

33:02.291 --> 33:04.259
(PIGS SQUEALING)

33:08.530 --> 33:10.332
(CHATTERING CONTINUES)

33:14.636 --> 33:16.740
(SOFT MEDIEVAL MUSIC
CONTINUES)

33:29.986 --> 33:31.386
(HORSE WHINNIES)

33:43.465 --> 33:45.601
(COUGHING)

33:46.736 --> 33:48.637
Sir Jean de Carrouges?

33:54.911 --> 33:56.678
Signature here.

34:06.723 --> 34:08.389
300 gold pieces.

34:22.638 --> 34:24.007
(HORSE WHINNIES IN DISTANCE)

34:28.377 --> 34:29.645
(DOG BARKS)

34:30.980 --> 34:32.447
MAN: Sire.

35:03.947 --> 35:05.849
I will be
in my chamber.

35:06.816 --> 35:08.117
Good night.

35:14.489 --> 35:15.691
My love?

35:18.560 --> 35:20.797
What is the matter?

35:20.864 --> 35:22.899
Has my mother quarreled
with you yet again?

35:25.400 --> 35:26.435
(SOFTLY) No.

35:31.406 --> 35:32.441
(DOOR OPENS)

35:33.642 --> 35:34.711
JEAN: I have missed you.

35:39.548 --> 35:42.451
Did you not miss me?

35:42.517 --> 35:44.153
(SIGHS) I missed you
more than you know.

35:44.220 --> 35:46.421
Then let us go to bed.

35:46.488 --> 35:48.091
- What? What is it, my love?
- I...

35:55.664 --> 35:56.966
Uh... (BREATHES SHAKILY)

36:01.037 --> 36:05.407
Uh, When...
When you were gone, there was a day

36:05.474 --> 36:08.477
when your mother had
business in Saint Pierre.

36:08.543 --> 36:09.645
Yes.

36:11.981 --> 36:16.819
She took the servants with her on
her errand, and I was left alone.

36:17.586 --> 36:19.155
Did she not
leave Alice?

36:19.222 --> 36:20.757
I told her in
no uncertain terms.

36:20.823 --> 36:22.892
She took
all the servants.

36:27.063 --> 36:30.199
Shortly after,
a man came unannounced.

36:32.601 --> 36:34.469
I knew the man,
so I let him in.

36:35.537 --> 36:37.040
But he was not alone.

36:41.811 --> 36:43.512
He attacked me.

36:46.581 --> 36:51.020
He pinned me down,
I protested.

36:51.087 --> 36:54.857
I screamed, I cried out as best I
could, but there was no one here.

36:56.591 --> 36:59.028
I was overpowered.
There was nothing I could do.

37:07.569 --> 37:08.972
I was raped.

37:11.207 --> 37:13.675
Who? Who did this?

37:14.210 --> 37:15.610
Who?

37:16.746 --> 37:17.780
Jacques Le Gris.

37:20.783 --> 37:21.818
(GASPS SOFTLY)

37:24.887 --> 37:27.156
Are you telling me
the truth?

37:27.223 --> 37:28.958
Yes. Yes.

37:29.025 --> 37:30.026
Are you telling me
the truth?

37:30.093 --> 37:31.094
Yes, I am telling you
the truth.

37:31.160 --> 37:32.829
You must believe me.

37:34.629 --> 37:35.664
You must.

37:37.834 --> 37:39.668
You are my beloved.

37:39.736 --> 37:40.737
Here.

37:43.672 --> 37:45.574
I was not here
to protect you.

37:46.743 --> 37:47.944
(JEAN SIGHS)

37:48.610 --> 37:50.113
Please forgive me.

37:52.215 --> 37:53.515
Please.

37:53.983 --> 37:55.251
Jean.

37:56.685 --> 37:59.621
I want him to answer
for what he has done.

38:00.256 --> 38:01.724
And he will.

38:04.761 --> 38:05.962
He will.

38:09.332 --> 38:10.767
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

38:10.833 --> 38:12.969
(SOMBER STRING MUSIC PLAYING)

38:14.070 --> 38:15.838
MAN 1: Collect the swords!

38:15.905 --> 38:17.140
MAN 2: Show them in, please.

38:18.174 --> 38:19.275
MAN 3: Take the horses down.

38:20.743 --> 38:21.978
Move them aside.

38:23.346 --> 38:24.747
MAN 2: Show them in, please.

38:24.814 --> 38:27.016
JEAN: <i>And so,
I ask for your help.</i>

38:27.083 --> 38:30.319
Marguerite is my wife,
and she has been wronged.

38:32.221 --> 38:34.190
I will not allow this
to go unpunished.

38:34.257 --> 38:37.126
Your only avenue
is through Pierre.

38:37.193 --> 38:39.062
Though I doubt he will
give you a hearing.

38:41.731 --> 38:44.000
Tell the story
you've heard today.

38:44.067 --> 38:46.869
Tell it anywhere you can
and to all who will listen.

38:46.936 --> 38:49.072
We will be the subject
of gossip.

38:49.138 --> 38:52.341
JEAN: If the story is known
across Normandy,

38:52.408 --> 38:54.576
Pierre will have to
grant us a hearing.

38:56.813 --> 38:58.147
I have a plan.

39:02.752 --> 39:04.120
(SPEAKS LATIN)

39:05.620 --> 39:07.156
(IN ENGLISH)
I request a duel to the death.

39:08.057 --> 39:10.893
This custom was outlawed
years ago.

39:11.394 --> 39:13.595
Not so, Your Grace.

39:13.662 --> 39:17.300
MAN: It is true that no duels have
been fought during your lifetime,

39:17.366 --> 39:20.069
though it remains
acceptable as a venue...

39:20.136 --> 39:21.938
JEAN: It would require
a full convening

39:22.004 --> 39:24.006
of the assembled
parliamentary body of Paris.

39:24.073 --> 39:26.843
All 32 members of
Your Majesty's court.

39:27.376 --> 39:28.978
One of us has lied.

39:30.012 --> 39:31.613
Let us let God decide.

39:31.680 --> 39:34.851
Sir Jean, if you
lose this duel,

39:34.917 --> 39:38.087
thus proving these
accusations false,

39:38.154 --> 39:40.389
your wife would suffer
dire consequences.

39:41.958 --> 39:44.827
God will spare those
who tell the truth.

39:44.894 --> 39:46.695
And the truth
will prevail.

39:47.430 --> 39:49.065
I am not afraid.

39:50.233 --> 39:51.400
Excellent.

39:53.069 --> 39:55.171
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

40:00.276 --> 40:02.677
(UNEASY MUSIC PLAYING)

40:20.730 --> 40:25.700
BAILIFF: His Majesty,
King Charles VI!

40:25.768 --> 40:29.005
KING CHARLES VI: What is your
business today before this court?

40:42.952 --> 40:45.121
Most excellent
and powerful king

40:45.188 --> 40:46.289
and our sovereign lord,

40:47.757 --> 40:49.825
I present myself,

40:49.892 --> 40:51.727
Jean de Carrouges,

40:51.794 --> 40:52.995
knight,

40:54.263 --> 40:56.399
as an appellant
in your court

40:57.867 --> 41:02.071
and hereby do
accuse this squire

41:02.138 --> 41:04.440
of a most foul crime

41:04.507 --> 41:06.742
against my wife,

41:06.809 --> 41:09.779
the Lady Marguerite de
Carrouges.

41:09.845 --> 41:13.249
I charge that during the third
week of this January past,

41:13.316 --> 41:15.218
this same Jacques Le Gris

41:16.519 --> 41:18.321
did feloniously

41:18.854 --> 41:20.156
and carnally

41:20.223 --> 41:24.193
take my wife against
her will in our house.

41:25.861 --> 41:29.799
And if this said
Jacques Le Gris

41:29.865 --> 41:32.368
denies his crime,

41:33.269 --> 41:35.404
I stand ready

41:35.471 --> 41:39.242
to prove my charge by
my body against his

41:39.308 --> 41:43.079
and to render him dead
at an appointed time.

41:49.785 --> 41:51.821
(COURT MEMBERS MURMURING)

42:00.997 --> 42:03.866
MAN: (LOUDLY)
Come for your fight!

42:03.933 --> 42:06.068
You're all gonna die!

42:07.036 --> 42:09.538
You're all gonna
die like pigs!

42:11.540 --> 42:13.843
Come on, then!

42:13.909 --> 42:16.345
Come on,
you failed scum...

42:16.412 --> 42:17.513
We cannot just sit here.

42:17.580 --> 42:19.115
MAN: ...and fight!

42:19.182 --> 42:21.484
Jean, we were ordered by
Pierre to hold this bridge.

42:21.550 --> 42:22.551
Orders be damned.

42:22.618 --> 42:24.220
JACQUES: They're baiting
you, Jean.

42:24.287 --> 42:26.055
They want us to leave the
bridge so they can take Limoges.

42:26.122 --> 42:28.891
(WOMEN CRYING AND SHRIEKING)

42:28.958 --> 42:30.926
Then they shall
have their wish!

42:32.328 --> 42:33.963
My son is a fool.
Let him go!

42:34.030 --> 42:35.364
If he goes alone,
he will die.

42:35.431 --> 42:37.133
For the king!

42:37.199 --> 42:38.334
ALL: For the king!

42:38.401 --> 42:40.369
(ALL YELLING)

42:44.106 --> 42:45.474
(MEN YELLING)

42:53.282 --> 42:55.518
(ALL GRUNTING AND YELLING)

43:08.030 --> 43:09.165
I know he is stubborn.

43:09.231 --> 43:11.233
PIERRE: Yes, stubborn,
difficult, jealous,

43:11.300 --> 43:14.203
- rash, dimwitted, irascible, dimwitted...
- Yes. Yes, yes, I know, milord.

43:14.270 --> 43:16.372
...stupid. He does not exactly
yield his rents on time.

43:16.439 --> 43:18.274
But I count him
as a friend.

43:18.341 --> 43:22.144
(SIGHS) He disobeyed me
and let Limoges fall.

43:22.211 --> 43:25.581
He believed he would succeed.
His intentions were good.

43:25.648 --> 43:28.584
He's no fucking fun.

43:28.651 --> 43:32.355
You mean, you'd like to see more
of his gloom here in Argentan?

43:32.421 --> 43:35.224
He postures and mopes about
like a black cloud.

43:35.291 --> 43:39.195
Milord, I have fought with him and
seen the worst of this world with him.

43:39.261 --> 43:41.497
- (SIGHS)
- He is loyal.

43:41.564 --> 43:43.599
Yeah. So are my
fucking hounds.

43:46.135 --> 43:48.904
As you wish. Take your leave.
Do as you like.

43:48.971 --> 43:51.474
I think very little
of his character.

43:51.540 --> 43:53.576
However, I think
a great deal of yours.

43:53.642 --> 43:56.479
It's the quality that most
recommends you.

43:56.545 --> 43:58.614
But do not let your loyalty
blind you.

44:01.050 --> 44:02.351
- Thank you, milord.
- Yes.

44:03.986 --> 44:05.654
Le Gris?

44:05.722 --> 44:08.557
The gold? Or the sandal?

44:09.558 --> 44:11.060
- Gold.
- Indeed.

44:11.127 --> 44:12.228
The gold.

44:12.295 --> 44:14.163
- (PLAYING LIVELY MUSIC)
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

44:18.234 --> 44:19.402
(LAUGHTER)

44:25.107 --> 44:27.076
MAN: No, no.
I know, I know...

44:27.143 --> 44:28.644
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

44:31.447 --> 44:33.215
Ladies and gentlemen.
(CLEARS THROAT)

44:33.282 --> 44:34.683
(MAN CLEARS THROAT LOUDLY)

44:37.586 --> 44:39.388
Ladies and gentlemen.

44:39.455 --> 44:44.527
Under ordinary circumstances,
your hostess, the viscountess,

44:44.593 --> 44:48.431
my wife,
Lady Marie Chamaillart,

44:48.497 --> 44:51.333
would see the sun come
up with all of us,

44:51.400 --> 44:53.502
sing louder,
dance more

44:53.569 --> 44:55.037
and drink you all
under the table.

44:55.104 --> 44:56.372
(GUESTS LAUGH)

44:56.439 --> 44:59.208
However, she's fast at work
growing our eighth child

44:59.275 --> 45:01.177
- in 14 years of marriage.
- (GUESTS GASP)

45:01.243 --> 45:03.045
(APPLAUSE)

45:05.481 --> 45:07.683
Well, good night,
dear friends.

45:07.751 --> 45:10.119
